< review>
Just finished week 4, first Lair visit.  Amazing!  Kids 5 & 9 did horseback riding, archery, pool time, exploring, kayaking, creek exploring, and paddle boating at the lake.  I did naps, pool, paddle boarding, kayaking, yoga, walk to the lake, tie-dye shirts, acrylic painting and ceramics.  They were generous and offered vegan foods for my diet restrictions.  Had a guitar lesson, met new friends in Oski's cabin circle.  Son said he loved the camp!  Carnival on Sunday was lots of fun, bounce houses and face painting.  So many activities!  Staff was super friendly and professional.< /review>

<UserId.>106721039165519242807</UserId.><name>Dottie Goldstein<//name><date>1471682138056</date><Rating>5< /Rating><text>I have camped at Lair with my own sons, and now I take my grandkids.
I love it. Lots to do, food is plentiful, staff is amazing.
I am baffled by all the negativity.
Health concerns:
I walk poorly. The EMT picked me up daily at my tent and brought me up to the Wellness Tent for the activities I chose. He was my uber driver. This was daily, twice a day!
My grandson was bitten by spiders, on two different days. The EMT was at our tent within minutes. At home, there would have been phone calls, dr. visits, etc. Lair is the place to need a dr., actually.</text>< pictures>

1422325129872<//Time>
<Rate>3<//Rate>< Text>
The first two years I attended the Lair Tennis and Golf camp, for the tennis,  I was delighted.  The tennis instruction was the best I have ever had, by far, as it featured three genuinely world class coaches -- Jan Brogan, Helle Viragh, and Steve Stefanki.
This last year (2014)  the Tennis camp was merged into a Sports and Recreation Camp.  Representations were made before and after the camp that the Tennis program would be and had been as good or better than ever.  It was, in fact, not close to what it was during my first two years, for two of the top three pros were absent and the third was less available than previously.
If you are thinking of going to the Sports and Recreation camp with the hope and expectation of receiving top flight tennis instruction you may  be disappointed.
The pros who staffed the camp during the 2014 season are all likeable people, and at least some are competent high school, club, and public court level instructors.  But they are not nearly at the level of the top pros I encountered my first two years.  Not only was the quality of the tennis instructional staff lower, but the amount of tennis activity was cut by half.
The tennis program aside, the camp is fine (if you don't mind being around a lot of heavy drinking).  As other reviewers have noted, the tents are rustic, but I found them comfortable.  The food is plentiful and good. The young staffers are generally delightful. The camp managers are concientious and responsive. The big trees are beautiful.  The facilities are clean.
If you are looking to just kick back for a week, lounge around a pool, get in a little tennis, meet some nice people and some zany people, join a drumming circle, take a few hikes, paddle around a lake in a plastic kayak,  and make a tie dye T-shirt of two, well, then at a $100 a day the Lair seems like a pretty good deal.  It's just not much of a tennis program anymore.  For half the money you can get far more  and far better tennis instruction by locating a top pro in your own neighborhood.</Text>

<Name>Adam O'Connor<//Name><date>1371586412378<//date>< rating>
4< /rating>
< text>
I am laughing at the negative reviews below! "No medical services...don't have a hear attack there." LOL. Who plans a heart attack. Don't know where this "expert" gets his information but there is nurse on staff in camp, and the camp contracts with Stanislaus County for emergency services. The service and response time for the LOTB is the same as any other private or public camp/resort in the Pinecrest area. No idea what the reviewer expects, a Level 1 trauma center? I have never seen, in 16 years, and injury that was not promptly and safely handled. That is BS to call it unsafe.

Also, what the camp staff (all energetic, bright, and fun college age kids) does or does not do at night is not really a concern of mine. They always are up early making coffee at 6:00 am for us, and never "party" in front of any campers. Of course they let off steam, just like me at that age.

I have been coming here as a camper since I was 22. I am a Cal alumni, and this is camp that is visited mostly by Cal alums and their families. My  wife and I had our first child at 25, and we now have four between 5-12. We have never missed a year. This is, hand-down, my families favorite place to spend a week in the woods. Most families return the same week each year, and we have a huge group of "Lair friends" we can't wait to see each year. In fact, for most weeks, there are waiting lists to get in. There are three camps, Oski, Gold, and Blue. Yes, it has gotten more expensive over 16 years. Google "inflation" if you are not clear on the concept.

They cook all 3 meals a day for you, the pool was just redone two years ago, they have restored the native meadows by removing extra roads, and they are remodeling all the bathrooms little by little. Plus the staff is there for whatever you might need. Sure, it is dusty, that is part of the fun. You can shower whenever you want, so what's the big deal?

Here is the real value and enjoyment  the priceless gift of babysitting from 9 am -12 pm, 1 pm-5 pm, and 6 pm-9 pm everyday. You see your kids for meals, so the staff can eat too. By "babysitting" I mean awesome activities that are planned by age group, so your kids are with kids their own age doing: nature walks in the creek, kayaking at the lake, arts and crafts, treasure hunts, pool parties, ghost stories, s'mores, movie night at Pinecrest Lake, inner tube water polo, kickball, capture the flag, disco bingo, hiking, softball, tie-die, lanyards, paddle tennis, etc. All of this is FREE and INCLUDED IN THE PRICE. How much do you think resorts charge for day-care? A LOT. So, when I factor in 7 days of babysitting for my 4 kids, this place is a GREAT deal.

Our kids have so much fun with the staff and their friends we barely see them some days, and that is fine. I can enjoy the quiet, fish, hike, bike, swim, or just nap, and everyone is happy. Unless you have been to the LOTB as a camper with kids you cannot understand how special this place is. I will be there soon, and I cannot wait. GO BEARS!< /text>

<user_id>114603918235035295760<//user_id><user_name>Jennifer DeVito-Patten (Purplegoddess)</user_name>< Date>
1596936744404<//Date>
<rating>5</rating>< text>
This is such a delightful store! It has everything you need to decorate your backyard for feeding birds & critters. Such pretty feeders that I had to get multiples. There are many beautiful & whimsical birdbaths; I must buy one soon. The owners & staff are always very friendly & knowledgeable. They are enthusiastic to help find the right feeders & accessories for your needs. I highly recommend to join their club. I think it's $25 for a year. It gives great discounts on your purchases and you can receive $10 in birdbucks to spend in the store. Every month I spend at least $150, and I get $10 in birdbucks which I used the following month. Sure you can buy cheaper bags of birdseed from big chain discount stores, but those bags are full of extra fillers that aren't eaten. For quality mixes of birdseed that doesn't go to waste and for excellent customer service, Wild Birds Unlimited is the best choice. It is a local small business that deserves our support.< /text>

<rate>5<//rate>< review>
I never realized how satisfying it is to cultivate a relationship with the birds in my own back yard until I stepped into this store! Not a single live bird in the store. Just well trained staff with a passion for helping people and well thought out products at reasonable prices. They can help you setup a single feeder to bring in a few hummingbirds or other wild birds or set you up with a whole system to bring birds by the flock to visit your yard. I highly recommend this store :-)< /review>

If I could give this place 0 stars I would. Continued to charge me for a year even though I canceled my membership.

I canceled my membership at the beginning of March in 2020 over the phone AND on their website. The charges temporarily stopped & I got charged twice in June, twice in October, and then they continued to charge me $30 a month consistently. I called again to get my money back (12/20), and we came to the agreement to just have a credit on my account and go with the basic membership ($13/mo). Since I moved I changed locations from the Folsom gym to the one off San Juan. When I checked my account again last night I saw that they are still charging me $30 a month! I called again just now and the manager said he has absolutely no record of me canceling my membership, or the agreement to do a credit because ‚Äúthere are no notes on (my) account.‚Äù All the manager offered to do to resolve the issue was cancel my membership.

<time>1526967852476</time><username>Ivan X</username><gmap_id>0x80c2bed55213acd1:0x757993f981204028<//gmap_id>< review>
Please read the entire review for the entire scope of my experience. I think they should be investigated for their practices and their methods of operation.

I think they not certified to repair many items they say they can repair and have no liability paperwork like any other business, yet they say they are backed up by having all the interactions on camera. I hope they save their footage because they are going to need it in small claims court.

So I take my phone into their store, replacing a battery for my phone. Since I could not make or wait a long appointment with Apple, I felt like the $6 difference in price was worth it. They charged $35 while Apple charged $29. I was getting my battery replaced for my Iphone 6+.

at 4pm I take it in and they tell me it's "only $35 if I pay cash". They say, "We don't want to deal with taxes and it's cheaper for you. it's good for both of us." I grumble because I am not carrying any cash. I ask if their is a Bank of America nearby. they tell me it's a few blocks away. i walk there to get cash out for the repair.

I get back and they said, "We opened the phone and it looks like your speaker is damaged" i said, "yes, it might be because it's inconsistent." they said, "we'll charge you $20 for that." i agree.

They finish and give me my phone. it turns on. i leave at 5:15pm

Note: I opened up the battery setting on the iphone and they Did fix the battery as that was registering. I figure that when they changed that, they messed up something else in the process.

When you get a new battery, the battery is never fully charged. I also waited until it got under 10% to charge it for the first time due to some possible myth of battery charging. It gets down to 5% and I charge it using the cord I used earlier in the day and many days before. The port felt snug. i look down and the phone wasn't charging. i adjust the cord and it still wasn't charging. "oh great. maybe they didn't tighten some screw or something inside" i call, they remember me and say, "oh okay. come back and we'll take care of you". This is at 6pm.

I head back and i'm there at 630pm, my phone was turned off because it was at 5% the last time I had it.

He said, "i told you I could change the charging port for you." I said, "No you didn't and it didn't need to be changed because That was working'.

So after some argument, another guy said, "When you have water damage, anything can go out at any time. it's wet right now". i said, "that's false in every way possible. the charging port was working when i brought it in and that false "water damage argument" just gives you full reign to not guarantee your work even though you told me you guarantee your work for 3 months". he said, "we don't guarantee something we don't fix".

He then said, "I don't want anymore problems so i'll just charge you the cost of the item." i said, "this is extortion but i guess I do not have any option". We argue a bit and he kept saying, "bro, you don't understand" while I was saying, "all i know is that it was working perfectly fine when i brought it in. it's like taking your car in to get your brakes fixed, you get your brakes fixed, you leave and your transmission goes out suddenly. it's probably not coincidental." I pay him through Venmo to skirt their desire for taxes. So he changes the charging port and he speaks another language to his customer and tells me, "it's the motherboard". i lose it because this just escalated into a worse case scenario solution. i said, "i want my money back and my phone as it was or you fixing my phone to working as it was when I brought it in".

They said, "we don't know what to tell you".

so After this, I need to make my voice heard and will do all legal things within my power to be fairly treated.

Be careful. They may fix something but make your situation worse, as they did for me. This was a nightmare and I hope none of you have to experience what I did. They should at least be investigated.< /review>

I started out with a cold that turned into an 11 week cough. I went into Urgent care and had a nurse practicioner (Veronica) who was super. She treated me for a sinus infection (after testing  me thoroughly)

Love this place!!.

<userid>118145333106853440318</userid>< Resp>
None</Resp>
<GmapID>0x80c33314b3dd2e31:0x2b25dcd666ed5d46< /GmapID>< Review>
Black Bear Diner is worth a visit for the atmosphere. Everything, from the building and entry way, to the waiting area, to the dining spaces, to the bathroom is on theme. Even the waitstaff are decked out in bear paw suspenders (available for purchase at the register).
Outside of the atmosphere, the experience is average. The 50s-newspaper style menu is cute, but the service is a bit slow. The food is well portioned and not too expensive, but the quality is nothing to write home about. The waitstaff is responsive, but not affable.
The redeeming feature of my dining experience was the desserts: the huckleberry ice cream is original (and tasty!) and the blackberry cobbler was delicious.
Overall, Black Bear Diner is worth a visit  for the experience or a drop-in when you're in the area anyhow, but it won't be replacing my local favorites. The novelty of its atmosphere may wear off, but it's a solid diner.</Review>

<Name>Julie Healon</Name>< time>

<rating>3< /rating><review>Eek! I hate leaving a 3 star rating for good food. But bad service cannot be ignored.

When we arrived, a lady named Preslee seated us. Very unpleasant. No smiles.  Very cold. I was hoping she wasn't our server. She was. üò£

She comes back a minute later, took our drink order. We said we needed a minute. She didn't come back for like 10 minutes. The place wasn't that busy. One half was even closed off.

Took 27 minutes for our food to come out. When she brought it, my husband had to ask for a refill. And extra napkins. Took over 5 minutes. We asked for some mayonnaise when she brought that. We never got it.

Finally came back, and we asked for a box. After 5 minutes, my husband just went and got one at the counter. A few minutes later, we got the bill. SUPER dissapointed in our service.

That aside, the food is amazing. This was our first time at this location. We've been to the one in Klamath Falls, Or. And to the one in Rohnert Park, Ca many times.

The food is always amazing. This visit, I ordered the cheddar bacon burger, add avocado.  Well well done. It was a tad pink inside. The meat was super thick, but It was manageable. It was a darn good burger. Very flavorful. The fries were ok. Nothing special. Didn't have any salt.

Hubby got the chicken fried steak dinner. It was super good. Huge portions. he upgraded to a loaded baked potato. Yummy! He got mixed veggies, which he didn't eat, since he never got the mayo he asked for, to eat with them.

He got the cheddar broccoli soup with a cornbread muffin. Both were good. The soup was super creamy, and flavorful.

We will be back, although we will definetly avoid Preslee.</review>< pictures>

< Name>

<Response>None</Response><userid>103920470896582208734</userid><pics>None< /pics><Rating>5< /Rating><gmap_id>0x80c33314b3dd2e31:0x2b25dcd666ed5d46</gmap_id><date>1553160313596<//date>< review>
Great regional chain diner! Excellent service. Cute, wonderfully kitschy bear motif throughout that makes me smile. I had a scramble, and there was a taco salad and a breakfast plate ordered at the table. Big Food. Excellent quality and delicious, so be not alarmed when you see massive plates on every table. Also feel free to ask for a box. They know how big their food is. They're cool about it. The service is friendly, attentive and prompt.

To anyone with food allergies, while they're not a specialized restaurant, the kitchen will work with you. I've developed a whole host of incredibly inconvenient food allergies (gluten, rice, peppers, potatoes, artificial dyes, most things that taste good...), and I was able to order a meal that was more than a salad without cobbling together twenty menu items. Our server made sure to note I have food sensitivities so I felt good about my meal prep without feeling like I was a pain... Wonderful! Thank you.

As a former diner dessert junkie, everything in the case looks like it's almost worth the misery (not quite) of the allergens inside... I can only imagine.</review>

<time>1537765674617</time><Rate>5</Rate>< review>
Outstanding food nice portions for the price your paying which by the way is reasonable. The pancakes themselves are worth the visit. Big and fluffy. They were very tasty the rest of the menu is also a hit. The atmosphere is very home like you feel comfortable here. The staff from the front all the way up to the manager is very friendly and helpful making sure your visit is a special one. If you get a chance jump off the 60 freeway on Mountain Avenue in Chino and look for the bear figures out front and come on in for good home cooked food. I guarantee you won't leave hungry.<//review>

< Text>
Servings are humongous.

The sweet potato fries are to die for and their bacon ranch is very mildly baconed so really good.

The waffles are more like pancakes. Which are good but not your typical waffle.

The cornbread is heavenly.

The chicken fried steak melts in your mouth.

The Mac and cheese is pennie with a white cheese sauce. Could be cheesier.

Their breakfast ham is a half inch+ thick and fairly lean.<//Text>

< text>
This review is for a delivery order (thru Postmates) from this location..

Steak & Eggs were unexpectedly tasty.  They were cooked as requested & suprisingly delivered better than expected.

One egg with sausage & pancake was equally delicious.  I normally get bacon but glad I tried their sausage.  It's so good!

Black Bear Diner also uses really nice to-go containers so don't worry about spills or messes.

Great food, delivery & service.</text>

<GmapID>0x80c33314b3dd2e31:0x2b25dcd666ed5d46</GmapID><username>Samantha Jimenez</username><Pictures>None</Pictures><rate>3< /rate><time>1502232632697< /time>< Review>
I've been here twice now, once with my husband, this last time with a party of 4. Both times the food was great, but it took FOREVER! We went this past Sunday morning, got there about 8am and there was no wait. Restaurant wasn't packed yet, so we figured we would be good. We all ordered breakfast, and waited for 45 minutes for our food. Food was really good!! Biscuits and gravy could have used a little more gravy, but very yummy! Our waitress kept our coffee mugs full the whole time, which was great, but to wait that long for breakfast was excessive.
I would like to come back here, but I hope their food service picks up.</Review>

Tonight was the worst experience I have had at Black Bear Diner in Chino.
At 8 pm. and the restaurant about half full my wife and I waited over 10 minutes to get seated.
The entire time we waited there were six plates of food setting up on the counter.
There were 3 families in line to pay for their bill and 2 groups of 2 waiting to get seated.
I was told that there were no clean tables.
So 2 hours before they close there was no one to clean the tables, no one to take the money and no one to seat you.
After 10 minutes of waiting with no one else ahead of me someone came up and asking for my name to put me on the list to get seated.
All this time there were 5 people in the kitchen.
We walked out and went to Corky's and enjoyed our dinner.<//text>

There were four of us. My two year old son was miserable because the flies kept landing on his head. My Mother-
In-law had flies land on her face and my wife and I had them land on us.
Every customer in the restaurant were swatting at flies. When I went to pay my bill--I asked to speak to the manager.
I assure you--I was Not trying to get out of paying my bill. I told Miguel-the manager--about the flies. He acted very surprised. Then he proceeded to tell me that they were working on it and that they had the exterminator there. Then he told me that there were lots of farms in the area. I explained to him that I lived on a dairy here in chino all of my life and that he needed to go to all of the surrounding restaurants and see that they Do Not have flies. Miguel was extremely rude and could care less about the flies and my complaint. I told him that I don't have flies in my kitchen at home and why would I come here to pay 50 dollars and fight the flies.
I will Never go back. Not appreciated.< /text>

<Text>Pancakes! Yummy, yummy SWEET CREAM pancakes!

That's all you need to know. But just in case the wait scares you... let me just say it's worth it. I drove by for months before actually going in. But now that I've gone, I wish I would've gone sooner.

I came on a weekday morning and was seated immediately. I had no idea what to order, so my waitress pointed out the sweet cream pancakes are the winner. And she was right!! My mouth is watering just thinking about it.

We also ordered an omelet, chicken fried steak and a philly sandwich. Everything was made well and delivered quickly. Good service, friendly smiles, fair prices! I'll be back. Thanks BBD!<//Text>< pics>

Pancakes! Yummy, yummy SWEET CREAM pancakes!

Update: Today, 3/5/2018 at 8:40 am I recieved the worst service of my life. I have never been treated with such indifference and lack of hospitality.

I walked in with my husband and this old man with his middle aged son are waiting with two other old men who were already there. The hostess asks us how many are in my party. I tell her two and this old man with a party of six which isn't even all together yet insists he be seated first so they can drink coffee. Okay. Fine. But the hostess never came back to seat us. We waited another 3 minutes for another server to come and seat us, which only happened because more customers had walked in already. We're taken to a table and given our drinks, server comes back to take our order and that's it. Food never came, my husband was never asked if he wanted more coffee. Meanwhile, the old men whose party isn't even complete are seated and enjoying coffee refills to their hearts content. The same hostess that never came to seat us walked passed us 6 times with TWO POT OF COFFEE. Needless to say we walked out.

<Review>This place doesnt take reservations so we asked if they can accommodate a group of 20, which they said they easily could. They sat us immediately but things were downhill from there. The orders were wrong, the food was average, two orders were forgotten, and it took forever for simple things like refills, ketchup, etc. We realize it's a newer location for this chain and anticipated slower service but the food was disappointing as well as the customer service. The waiter tried very hard to do as much as he could but he literally had no help. The manager didnt come over until we requested her, even then she was very reluctant to offer support to the waiter. We've eaten at other Black Bear restaurants in Northern California but this location's service and especially food were VERY disappointing.<//Review>< Pics>

< Review>
This place doesnt take reservations so we asked if they can accommodate a group of 20, which they said they easily could. They sat us immediately but things were downhill from there. The orders were wrong, the food was average, two orders were forgotten, and it took forever for simple things like refills, ketchup, etc. We realize it's a newer location for this chain and anticipated slower service but the food was disappointing as well as the customer service. The waiter tried very hard to do as much as he could but he literally had no help. The manager didnt come over until we requested her, even then she was very reluctant to offer support to the waiter. We've eaten at other Black Bear restaurants in Northern California but this location's service and especially food were VERY disappointing.< /Review>

<user_id>105143565502680050516< /user_id><user_name>Burn Dup</user_name><Date>1513197008645</Date>< rate>
2</rate>
< Review>
Friends had hyped this place up pretty good, as they found it years before in far-Northern CA after emerging from the wilderness during a camping trip.

The theme is log-cabin-y, and the food is traditional "American Comfort Food" served in very large portions. Fortunately, they offer downsized (aka normal sized) portions of most of their dishes. I opted for this smaller serving of their meatloaf, as it was getting late in the evening.

It was good, it's hard to screw up meatloaf and mashed potatoes with gravy. The bacon beans tasted like they had sat in tupperware too many days after coming out of the can. Salad was food-service iceberg with generic food-service creamy blue cheese.

Where this place truly fell on it's face was service. Restaurant was at less than 25% capacity on a Tuesday evening, and it took over 30 minutes after ordering for our group of 7 to be served our meals. We were not an intimidating group, but the three waitresses working our particular dining room were scarce, and seemed to avoid our party, as if they thought we'd be extra work. So just as I was about to give up ordering a chocolate malt for dessert, I finally flagged a waitress down. 15 minutes later, I was served a ginormous, yet absolutely ordinary chocolate malt, when I should have been going to bed.

For a new place, the carpet had some gnarly stains, and the restroom was out of paper towels.

Their menu is a little newspaper-type thing. One "article" on the front page details the chain's absolutely cancerous growth in the last ten years, citing all of the diners they have opened up in various cities, with the rate of maliginancy exponentiating in the last two years.

Like any cancer, this growth will be soon fatal if they don't have proper management overseeing the twentysomethings that scurry around and crew this diner. Such management was clearly not present the evening of my visit.<//Review>
